23 (c) (1) Members of the task force shall be residents of Kansas. The
24 task force shall consist of at least two members one member from all each
25 of the five conservation regions of the state. Not more than two members
26 of the task force shall represent the same stakeholder enumerated in
27 subsection (b).
28 (2) The speaker of the house of representatives and the president of
29 the senate shall ensure that the requirements of paragraph (1) are met.
30 (d) Members of the task force shall be appointed by April 30, 2025.
31 Any vacancy in the membership of the task force shall be filled by
32 appointment in the same manner prescribed by this section for the original
33 appointment.
34 (e) The speaker of the house of representatives shall select one
35 member of the task force who is a member of the house of representatives
36 to serve as co-chairperson of the task force. The president of the senate
37 shall select one member of the task force who is a member of the senate to
38 serve as co-chairperson of the task force.
39 (f) (1) The task force may meet at any time and at any place within
40 the state upon the call of either co-chairperson.
41 (2) A majority of voting members shall constitute a quorum of the
42 task force. All actions of the task force may be taken by a majority of
43 members present when there is a quorum.

HB 2172—Am. by HCW 4
1 (3) If approved by the legislative coordinating council, members of
2 the task force attending meetings authorized by the task force shall be paid
3 amounts for expenses, mileage and subsistence as provided in K.S.A. 75-
4 3223(e), and amendments thereto.
5 (4) The staff of the office of revisor of statutes, the legislative
6 research department and the division of legislative administrative services
7 shall provide such assistance as may be requested by the task force.
8 (g) The water program task force shall:
9 (1) Evaluate major risks to the quality and quantity of the state's
10 water supply, including any impact on current and future economic growth
11 and population stability;
12 (2) steps that the state must take to define and achieve an ongoing,
13 multigenerational promise of water for Kansans; and
14 (3) evaluate current funding for water in the state and determine
15 whether such funding is sufficient to address the water issues included in
16 the state water plan, including the state's current and future water
17 infrastructure needs.
18 (h) The task force shall prepare and submit a report to the legislature
19 and the governor on or before January 31, 2026. Such report shall include
20 recommendations on:
21 (1) The water program's long-term structure to address the state's
22 current and future water needs, including, but not limited to:
23 (A) The roles and responsibilities of the state, municipalities and
24 regional entities;
25 (B) how the program's investments and successes should be
26 evaluated, including gathering any stakeholder input; and
27 (C) criteria to determine program investments, including geographic
28 diversity of such investments; and
29 (2) funding for the water program, including, but not limited to:
30 (A) New dedicated moneys or investments for the state water plan
31 fund;
32 (B) changes to any existing fees or moneys dedicated to the state
33 water plan fund; and
34 (C) any additional funding sources or tools necessary to ensure that
35 the financial resources are adequate to address the state's water issues.
36 (i) This section shall expire on July 1, 2027.
37 Sec. 2. This act shall take effect and be in force from and after its
38 publication in the Kansas register.

